# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
traverse through matrix hit right when you hit a visited node or go out of limits. break when count goes to n^2 +1.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
maintain n*n matrix. change direction when you hit a visited node or go out of limits. increment count after every insertion 

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->O(N2)

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->O(N2)

Please upvote if you find it helpful 

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    vector<vector<int>> generateMatrix(int n) {

        vector<vector<int>> visited(n, vector<int>(n, 0)); int c = 1; 
        vector<vector<int>> res(n, vector<int>(n, 0));  int x = 0; int y = 0;   char d = 'r'; 
        while( c != n*n+1){
            if(d == 'r'){
                res[x][y] = c;  visited[x][y] = 1; y++; c++; 
                if(y>=n||visited[x][y] == 1) {y--; x++; d = 'd'; continue;  }
            }
            else if(d == 'd'){
                res[x][y] = c; visited[x][y] = 1; x++; c++; 
                if(x>=n || visited[x][y] == 1) {x--; y--; d = 'l'; continue; }
            }
            else if(d == 'l'){
                res[x][y] = c; visited[x][y] = 1; y--; c++;
                if(y<0 || visited[x][y] == 1) { y++; x--; d = 'u'; continue; }
            }
            else if(d == 'u'){
                res[x][y] = c; visited[x][y] = 1; x--; c++;
                if(x<0 || visited[x][y] == 1) {x++; y++; d = 'r'; continue; }
            }
        }

        // cout << x << y << d ; 

        return res; 
    }
};
```

