# Intuition

Easy approach to solve this question :) 🔥.

We mainly focus on the `top row`, `right column`, `bottom row` & `left column` after creating a blank matrix.
After every iteration we increamnt `starting row` & `starting column` and decrement `ending row` & `ending column`.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

- **Creating** a blank matrix of size m.
`int[][] ans = new int[n][n];`
- **Initializing** the values for smooth travelling in the matrix 
```
int startingRow = 0;
int endingRow = n - 1;
int startingCol = 0;
int endingCol = n - 1;
```
- For **Top Row** `Left -> Right` -> as we go left to right then we increament the values then we go to next row. i.e. `startingRow++`
```
for (int i = startingCol; i <= endingCol; i++) {
        ans[startingRow][i] = count;
        count++;
    }
    startingRow++;
```
- For **Right Column** `Top-->Bottom` --> after the top row, for every next row we go with the last index value of every column, till last second row. Then decrement the ending column index  i.e. `endingCol--`.
```
for (int i = startingRow; i <= endingRow; i++) {
        ans[i][endingCol] = count;
        count++;
    }
    endingCol--;
```
- For **Bottom Row** `Right-->LEft` --> we go right to left then we decrement the ending column variable. i.e. `endingCol--`.
```
for (int i = endingCol; i >= startingCol; i--) {
        ans[endingRow][i] = count;
        count++;
    }
    endingRow--;
```
- For **Left Column** `Bottom-->Top` --> after the botto row, for every above row we go with the first index value till the top second row. Then we increment the first index of every column i.e. `startingCol++` . 
```
for (int i = endingRow; i >= startingRow; i--) {
        ans[i][startingCol] = count;
        count++;   
    }
    startingCol++;
```

# Complexity
- Time complexity:$$O(n^2)$$
