# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The intuition behind this solution is to use four loops, each representing a direction (right, down, left, up) to fill the matrix in a spiral order. The loops move along the outer boundaries of the matrix and increment the current number to be filled.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
- Initialize variables: total to store the total number of elements in the matrix, result to store the generated matrix, x and y as the current positions in the matrix, and step to keep track of the current boundary step.
- Use a loop that runs until i reaches the total number of elements.
- Within the loop, move right until reaching the end of the current row, fill the current position with the next number, and increment i.
- Adjust the position and repeat the process for moving down, left, and up, respectively.
- Update step after completing one spiral loop to move to the inner boundaries of the matrix.
- Repeat the steps until all elements are filled.
- Return the generated matrix.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The time complexity of this solution is O(n^2), where n is the given input. It iterates over each element in the matrix exactly once.

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The space complexity is O(n^2) as well since the solution creates a 2D matrix of size n x n to store the generated matrix.

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int[][] generateMatrix(int n) {
        int total = n*n;
        int[][] result= new int[n][n];
        int x=0;
        int y=0;
        int step = 0;
        for(int i=0;i<total;)
        {
            while(y+step<n)
            {
                i++;
                result[x][y]=i;
                y++;
            }
            y--;
            x++;
            while(x+step<n)
            {
                i++;
                result[x][y]=i;
                x++;
            }
            x--;
            y--;
            while(y>=0+step)
            {
                i++;
                result[x][y]=i;
                y--;
            }
            y++;
            x--;
            step++;
            while(x>=0+step)
            {
                i++;
                result[x][y]=i;
                x--;
            }
            x++;
            y++;
        }
        return result;

    }
}
```

