solutions.content:
To find repeating substring, information about the frequency of each character helps a lot.

Let's take `babbaaabbbbabbaaabbbbabbaaabbb` as an example, 
the frequencies of each character are

```txt
a : 12
b : 18
```

Of those frequences, `min = 12`, `max = 18`.

There are few obvious cases that can be eliminated
1. if `max` equals the string length, we can infer that there is only one unique character in the string, so if the length is greater than 1, the string repeats n times. Example: `aaaaa`.
2.  If `min` is equal to 1, there is a character that occurs only once, which is not possible if a repetition exists. Example: `abcabcd`.

If we calculate the GCD of `min`, `max` we can know the upper bound on the number of possible repetitions. If GCD equals 1, it means that no common divisor is found and hence no repetitions are possible.

`GCD(min, max) = GCD(12, 18) = 6`

If there are 6 possible repetitions, then the pattern size should be equal to `string.length / 6 => 30 / 6 = 5` 
Pattern size 5, `babba` is not the pattern that's repeating, so we move on to the multiples of 6 `[3, 2]`

If there are 3 repetitions, then the pattern size will be equal to `string.length / 3 => 30 / 3 = 10`
Pattern size 10 `babbaaabbb` is the repeating pattern.


```java
class Solution {
    public boolean repeatedSubstringPattern(String s) {
        int min = Integer.MAX_VALUE, max = Integer.MIN_VALUE;
        int[] c = new int[26];

        // count frequency of each character
        for (int i=0; i<s.length(); i++) {
            c[s.charAt(i) - 'a']++;
        }

        // calculate max, min frequency
        for (int i=0; i<c.length; i++) {
            if (c[i] > 0) {
                if (c[i] < min) {
                    min = c[i];
                }
                if (c[i] > max) {
                    max = c[i];
                }
            }
        }

        // if a character frequency == string length,
        // there is only one unique character in the entire string
        if (max == s.length()) {
            return max > 1;
        }

        // min must be >= 2 for repetition to occur
        if (min <= 1) {
            return false;
        }

        // GCD gives an upper bound on the possible number of repetitions
        int repeatCount = GCD(min, max);

        // If no common divisor > 1, repetition not possible
        if (repeatCount == 1) {
            return false;
        }

        List<Integer> multiples = new ArrayList<Integer>();
        multiples.add(repeatCount);
        multiples.addAll(getMultiples(repeatCount));

        // for each multiple of GCD, check if pattern repeats
        for (int i : multiples) {
            if (isRepeating(s, i)) {
                return true;
            }
        }

        return false;
    }

    int GCD(int a, int b) {
        return a == 0 ? b : GCD(b%a, a);
    }

    List<Integer> getMultiples(int n) {
        List<Integer> list = new ArrayList<Integer>();
        for (int i=n/2; i>=2; i--) {
            if (n % i == 0) {
                list.add(i);
            }
        }
        return list;
    }

    boolean isRepeating(String s, int repeatCount) {
        int patternLength = s.length()/repeatCount;
        String pattern = s.substring(0, patternLength);
        for (int i=1;i<repeatCount; i++) {
            int begin = patternLength * i;
            int end = begin + patternLength;
            if (!s.substring(begin, end).equals(pattern)) {
                return false;
            }
        }
        return true;
    }
}
```

