# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The idea behind the solution is to consider all possible substring lengths that could potentially form the repeated pattern. For each candidate substring length, we check if it can be used to construct the entire string by appending multiple copies of it together.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1. We iterate through the possible substring lengths from 1 to half the length of the input string (n / 2). This is because a substring of length greater than half the length of the string cannot be used to form a repeated pattern.

1. For each substring length (len), we check if the length of the input string is divisible by len. If it is, then it's possible that a repeated pattern of length len could form the entire string.

1. We extract the candidate substring of length len from the beginning of the input string.

1. We construct a new string by repeating the candidate substring the necessary number of times (n / len times).

1. We compare the newly constructed string with the original input string. If they match, then the input string can be formed by repeating the candidate substring, and we return true.

1. If no candidate substring length leads to a match, we return false.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The time complexity of this solution can be analyzed as follows:

- We iterate through possible substring lengths from 1 to n / 2, where n is the length of the input string. This takes O(n) time.
- For each candidate substring length, we construct a new string by repeating the substring n / len times. Constructing this new string takes O(n) time in the worst case.
- Comparing the newly constructed string with the input string also takes O(n) time.
- Therefore, the overall time complexity is approximately O(n^2) in the worst case.

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The space complexity is determined by the space used for the candidate substring and the space used for constructing the new string. Both of these can take up to O(n) space in the worst case (when the candidate substring is the entire string itself).

Hence, the overall space complexity is O(n).

# Code
```
public class Solution {
    public bool RepeatedSubstringPattern(string s) {
        int n = s.Length;

        for (int len = 1; len <= n / 2; len++) {
            if (n % len == 0) {
                string sub = s.Substring(0, len);
                StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();

                for (int i = 0; i < n / len; i++) {
                    sb.Append(sub);
                }

                if (sb.ToString() == s) {
                    return true;
                }
            }
        }

        return false;
    }
}
```

