### Solution 1: recursive

```
    static int maxDepth(const Node* root) {
        if (!root) return 0;
        int max_child = 0;
        for (const Node* child : root->children) {
            max_child = max(max_child, maxDepth(child));
        }
        return 1 + max_child;
    }
```

### Solution 2: iterative DFS/BFS

This is the DFS solution, but we could just replace the ```stack``` with a ```queue``` and we would have a BFS solution.

```
    static int maxDepth(const Node* root) {
        if (!root) return 0;

        stack<pair<const Node*, int>> st;
        st.push({root, 1});
        int ans = 1;
        while (!empty(st)) {
            const auto [node, depth] = st.top(); st.pop();
            ans = max(ans, depth);
            for (const Node* child : node->children) {
                st.push({child, depth + 1});
            }
        }
        return ans;
    }
```

### Solution 3: level order traversal (BFS)

This was inspired by a submission from @pan_vis98.

```
    static int maxDepth(const Node* root) {
        if (!root) return 0;

        queue<const Node*> q;
        q.push(root);
        int ans = 0;
        while (!empty(q)) {
            int q_size = size(q);
            while (q_size--) {
                const Node* node = q.front(); q.pop();

                for (const Node* child : node->children) {
                    q.push(child);
                }
            }
            ++ans;
        }
        return ans;
    }
```

