__Thank you for checking out my solution, Do Upvote if it helped :)__

__"The transpose of a matrix is the matrix flipped over its main diagonal, switching the matrix's row and column indices".
Therefore the idea here is to to fill all the row elements of the given matrix as the column elements of the transpose matrix
or the columns elements of the given matrix as the row elements of the transpose matrix.__

__Had the given constraints stated that the matrix is square, we could have solved the question in-place.
Even now it is possible (not exactly in-place, but without creating a new matrix) as we shall see in the next approach, but its not very intuitive.__

__Approach 1 (Recommended):__

>Create a matrix which has
>>rows = columns of the given matrix 
>>columns = rows of the given matrix
>>i.e. if the given matrix has dimensions [R x C], then our answer matrix will have dimensions as [C x R]

>Now Simply Run the loops
>>Outer loop from i = 0 to i = column number
>>>Inner loop from j = 0 to j = row number, (you can reverse them too)
>>>Fill answer[i][j] = matrix [j][i] , [change matrix with answer, if you reverse the above mentioned two loops]

>Now return the answer matrix!

__Below is the cpp implementation of the above mentioned approach__


```
class Solution {  // Runtime: 8 ms, faster than 95.19% of C++ online submissions for Transpose Matrix.
                  // Memory Usage: 10.6 MB, less than 43.03% of C++ online submissions for Transpose Matrix.
public:
    vector<vector<int>> transpose(vector<vector<int>>& matrix) 
    {
         int x = matrix.size(), y = matrix[0].size();          //getting the number of rows and columns 
         vector<vector<int>> res(y,vector<int>(x));            //Creating a transpose matrix [columns x rows]
         for(int i = 0; i < y;i++)
             for(int j = 0;j < x; j++)
                 res[i][j] = matrix[j][i];                     //Filling the matrix, (i,j)th cell in res is to be filled with (j,i)th cell in matrix
        return res;
    }
};
```
__Time Complexity : O(Rows * Columns) ~ O(N^2)
Space Complexity : O(Rows * Columns) ~ O(N^2)__
>.
>.
_____
__Approach 2 (Just to make the question slightly tough):__

__As mentioned before, had the given constraints stated that the matrix is square, we could have solved the question in-place and in less time(jth loop will begin from i). This is because then we would have just swapped the current element and the element on the other side of the diagonal
i.e. (i,j)th element with the (j,i)th element.
And since there would have been a symmetry(shape of a square matrix is not affected by rotation), there would have been no issues with the dimensions.__

__Since it won't always be a square, so you can take min of (rows, columns), swap the values by running both the loops to this minimum
But this only works for the matrix of dimension [(min) x (min)], 
And now the problem begins:
if rows < columns:__
>__(Its More Problematic)
>Iterate i from min(R,C) to C
>Initialise a temporary vector v__
>>Iterate j from 0 to R(rows)
>>Keeping pushing the (j)th [current] column elements into a temporary vector
>
>__Now Push this temporary vector into the matrix
>Now that the elements are all pushed, resize the vectors from 0 to MIN, with size(R)__

__if rows > columns__
>__(Its Relatively easier)
>Iterate i from 0 to min(R,C)__
>>Iterate j from min(R,C) to R
>>Keeping pushing the extra column elements in the (i)th column to the (i)th row
>
>__Now Resize the matrix to C columns, Since all the rows will with less elements are to be ignored, simply resize to C__

__Return the current matrix, here we altered the current matrix to get its transpose__
____
Below is the cpp implementation of the above mentioned Approach



```
class Solution
{ // Runtime: 20 ms, faster than 27.23% of C++ online submissions for Transpose Matrix.
  // Memory Usage: 10.6 MB, less than 43.03% of C++ online submissions for Transpose Matrix.
public:
    vector<vector<int>> transpose(vector<vector<int>> &matrix)
    {
        int R = matrix.size(), C = matrix[0].size(); // getting the number of rows and columns
        int MIN = min(R, C), diff = abs(R - C);
        for (int i = 0; i < MIN; i++)     // For a square matrix , just swapping the (i,j)th cell with (j,i)th cell works
            for (int j = i; j < MIN; j++) // The dimension is halved because (j,i)th cell is on the other side of the diagonal
                swap(matrix[i][j], matrix[j][i]);
        if (R < C) // When rows < columns, resizing is an issue
        {
            for (int i = MIN; i < C; i++)
            {
                vector<int> v;
                for (int j = 0; j < R; j++) // Combining extra columns elements to a since vector
                    v.push_back(matrix[j][i]);
                matrix.push_back(v); // Adding this combine column vector as a new row to the matrix
            }
            // Resizing as [C x R]
            for (int i = 0; i < MIN; i++) // Resize all the rows with extra elements
                matrix[i].resize(R);
        }
        else if (C < R)// When rows < column, it gets easier
        {
            for (int i = 0; i < MIN; i++)
                for (int j = MIN; j < R; j++)
                    matrix[i].push_back(matrix[j][i]); // All the extra column elements in the (i)th column,will be pushed to (i)th row
            matrix.resize(C);                          // Since all the rows will with less elements are to be ignored, simply resize to C
        }
        return matrix;
    }
};
```
__Time Complexity : O(Rows * Columns) ~ O(N^2)
Space Complexity : O(Rows * Columns) ~ O(N^2)__

