So, the first thing is, we should probably ignore the metrics. It's not always correct. And in this case we just have to re-submit again and again till it gets submitted in a time interval when leetcode system is not overloaded.

**Although in this case, it's the variable name length.**

Look at this 100% solution:
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/3d14b9af-2efa-4a48-bb6f-fb67b8fd43cd_1654142251.6377287.jpeg)

Look at 52.16% one: 
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/2083a5f0-7943-4895-86b0-6647a70ffd0d_1654142270.584384.jpeg)

matrixT is a longer variable name compared to ans. It’s a tradeoff between having a readable code and saving a small fraction of time.

Let's try making the same matrixT as X and see:
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/f31f1222-1819-4b9e-a22f-e9b75c2791f7_1654142798.5085976.png)

**Ignoring all these factors, coming to the code if it's unclear:**
What's a transpose?
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/24583cce-5b43-4fbf-a48f-2d6df52f7c26_1654142395.7688913.png)
So, basically we are exchanging the values. Note, we can't do inplace as we require the values of the matrix in the future. Hence the SC will always remain O(R*C)

Now, as for the code:
```
class Solution {
    public int[][] transpose(int[][] matrix) {
        int m=matrix[0].length;
        int n=matrix.length;
        int matrixT[][] = new int[m][n];
        for (int i=0; i<m;i++)
        {
            for (int j=0; j<n;j++)
            {
                matrixT[i][j]=matrix[j][i];
            }
        }
        return matrixT;
    }
}
```

