# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
So if think of naive approach that can be done by checking all the subarrays are dvisible by k or not .And that will be done by using two two loops in O(n^2). So we dont want TLE ,so we have to optimize..
So directly coming to point there is a property of prefix sum here that if we subtract two pref sums and they are divsible by k then their individual remainders are same i.e
`If (Pref[i]-Pref[j])%k==0 `
`then pref[i]%k==pref[j]%k`
can be easily proved using `number = divisor \xD7 quotient + remainder`
so `pref[i]=d*qi +r1`
   `pref[j]=d*qj +r2`
   `pref[i]-pref[j]`=`d*(qi-qj) +(r1-r2)`
  d*(qi-qj) is already divisble by k now if `(r1-r2)%k=0`
 Since r1 and r2 are both less than k  so `r1=r2;`
 So if two prefix sums have same remainders they are also divisble by k 
So After All this main idea is if two pref sums have same remainder they add  up to answer because the subarray between them have sum divisible by k 
e.g
k=3
 aray nums: 1 3 `5 4` 5 6 7
 pref sums: 1 4 9 13 18 24 31
taking this 1 4 `9 13` 18 24 31
we know 13 -4 = 9 %3=0
applying property 13%3=1 and 4%3 =1
so subarray between 4 and 13 pref sum will be divible by k
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
So we can loop through the array and store a prefix sum in a variable and keep checking its remainder if its same with other it will add up to our answer . 
We need to store the occurences of remainder in an array of size k beacuse remainders are form `o to k-1` .
And we also need to initialize pref[0]=1 because whole array can be divisible or individual pref sums can be divisible by k (i.e when ever remanider is zero )
