Note that this solution has O(n * n) worst case complexity; but I got stuck during the contest and this is was the best I could come up with :)

If we find a sum divisible by K at index ```i```, then we can just add the number of subarrays for interval [i + 1, n). So, if we start from the end of the array, and record number of subarrays for each index, then for the next index ```i``` we only need to check till we find the first divisible sum ```[i, j]```, and add pre-calculated number of subarrays for index ```j + 1```.

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/votrubac/image_1589515276.png)

```
int subarraysDivByK(vector<int>& A, int K) {
  vector<int> dp(A.size() + 1, 0);
  for (int i = A.size() - 1; i >= 0; --i)
    for (int j = i, sum = 0; j < A.size(); ++j) {
      sum += A[j];
      if (sum % K == 0) {
        dp[i] = 1 + dp[j + 1];
        break;
      }
    }
  return accumulate(begin(dp), end(dp), 0);
}
```

