## Explanation:

### Solution 01

- If we modular any number with ***k*** the result will always be less than k.
- Here we took a ***k*** size array to store the number of occurrences of every number from 0 to k.
- From start to end we’ll count the occurrences, if ***index 2 have modules value 3 & also index 5 have the same value, then from 2 to 5 elements will be divisible with k.***
- To store the sum we’ll first mod the element, but that could be negative. So, if we add k with it and mod it again it will be positive.
- Them in the array mp, we’ll store all the occurrence count. We’ve done ***sum%k*** because the sum value could be greater than k, by this we’ll keep it in our range.
- Then we’ll traverse the array and use the formula ***nC2,*** to calculate the total number.
- Edge case: for 0 the formula is ***nC2+n.*** We added the no of 0th element in the count array before starting to avoid this extra calculation.
- **Time complexity:** O(n).

---

