solutions.content:
We don't need to find subarrays with sum K , rather we need to find subarrays with sum divisible by K.

So, using remainder theorem is useful here.

If we have an index i, whose prefixsum(i) % k = x, 
and index j, whose prefixsum(j) % k = x,

then from remainder theorem, 
**(prefixsum(i) - prefixsum(j))% k = x - x = 0**

**That is, the subarray (i , j] has a sum which is divisible by k**

Once we understand this logic, our goal is to find frequency of all such indices, whose prefix sum % k is the same, because the subarray enclosed by any 2 such indices will yield a sum divisible by k.
For instance, if I have 5 indices whose prefix sum % k is 1, then choosing any 2 of them yields a unique subarray whose sum is divisible by k.
So, the formula nC2 can be used, where n is the frequency calculated.

Here is the code with explanations:
```
class Solution {
public:
    int subarraysDivByK(vector<int>& nums, int k) {

        vector<int> check(k , 0);// stores frequency of (running sum % k)

        int n = nums.size();
        int running_sum = 0;

        check[0] = 1; // important to know that running sum is 0 before starting!

        for(int i = 0 ; i < n ; i++){

            running_sum += nums[i];

            int rem = (k + (running_sum % k)) % k;//for handling negative mod, a % b is same as (b + (a % b)) % b

            check[rem]++;//incrementing the frequency of that modulus
        }

        int res = 0;

        for(int i = 0 ; i < k ; i ++){

            int x = check[i];//x now stores the number of indices whose (running sum % k) is i

            res += (x * (x - 1)) / 2; 
            // nC2 is used as any two indices with same modulus can be chosen to make a subarray whose sum is multiple of k
        }

        return res;

    }
};
```

