# Explanation

1.This problem is similar to subarray with sum equal to K.
2.There, We calculate sum for every element. We check if that sum is already in the hashmap,if yes means we have encountered subarray with that sum.
3.This works because if  two positions i,j in an array and if  sum[j]-k = sum[i] ,means 
 sum[j]-sum[i] = k .Hence we we get (2.)

 Similarly, Applying same analogy to division by K,
 If at two positions in an array if sum/k leaves same remainder, then means sum[j]-sum[i] if divisible by k;

Lets understand with one example,

 Let sum[i] = 5 and k = 3
	 sum[i]%k = 2     -----(1)-------
 Also, sum[j] = 14 
	 sum[j]%k =  2   -----(1)-------

 So,essentially, sum[j]-sum[i] has to be equla to k inorder to have same remainder at ith and jth position.

**Edge Case**
 if sum is -ve, then its remainder will not be sum%K,

 we have to do (sum + k)%k, to get its correct remainder.
(why ? try with some examples , you will get it ) 

One more case can be sum+k still < 0,then you can do
sum = -(abs(sum)%k);
Now if you do (sum_k)%k, you will get right remainder.

(This might be confusing at first, try with some more examples and dry run for more clarity :) )



