solutions.content:
## Approach 1: O(n+k) time and O(k) space 
**Intuition:** If prefix sum till index i=Si and prefix sum till index j=Sj,
Then, if Si%k=rem1 and Sj%k=rem2
if both sums leave same remainder, 
Si%k=Sj%k => (Sj%k-Si%k)Si%k=0 
That means subarray sum from (i+1) to j will be divisible by k;
```
 nums [i]                    = [ 4  5  0  -2  -3  1  ] and k=5
 prefix sum till index i     = [ 4  9  9   7   4  5  ]
 prefix sum till index i%k   = [ 4  4  4   2   4  0  ]
```
Now if n terms of prefix sum leave the same remainder, means you may choose any 2 of them ans subarray between them will be div by k. So count the prefix sum in each residue class. In above example-
```
residue class : count : countC2
0             |   1   | 0
1             |   0   | 0
2             |   1   | 0
3             |   0   | 0
4             |   4   | 4C2=6 
```
Now for each residue class calculate how much subsets in between them vy nC2=count * (count-1)/2

Now add the subarrays with prefix sum as 0 directly(whole prefix divisible by k)= 1

so total count here will be 0+0+0+0+6+1=7
```
class Solution {
public:
    int subarraysDivByK(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
        long long sum=0;
        vector<int> residueclass(k,0);
        for(auto &n:nums){
            sum+=n;
            int rem=sum%k;
            if(rem<0)rem+=k;
            residueclass[rem]++;
        }
        sum=residueclass[0];

        while(k--){
            sum+=(long long)residueclass[k]*(residueclass[k]-1)/2;
            // cout<<i<<","<<sum<<" ";
        }
        return sum;
    }
};
```
## Approach 2: O(n) time and O(k) space 
We can optimize the above approach by 
1. avoiding multiplications and doing additions
2. making solution O(n) independent of k in time complexity

**Intuition:** whenever we get a residue of prefix_sum[i] we match it with the prefix_sum of same residue class that occured before element i. Eg
```
 nums [i]                    = [ 4  5  0  -2  -3  1  ] and k=5
 prefix sum till index i     = [ 4  9  9   7   4  5  ]
 prefix sum till index i%k   = [ 4 ] // 4 residue not occured before
 prefix sum till index i%k   = [ 4  4 ] // 4 occured 1 times before, 1 eligible subset [5]
 prefix sum till index i%k   = [ 4  4  4 ]// 4 occured 2 times before, 2 eligible subset [5, 0] and [0]
 prefix sum till index i%k   = [ 4  4  4   2 ]// 2 residue not occured before
 prefix sum till index i%k   = [ 4  4  4   2   4 ]// 4 occured 3 times before, 3 eligible subset [5, 0, -2, -3], [0, -2, -3], [-2, -3]
 prefix sum till index i%k   = [ 4  4  4   2   4  0  ]// 0 residue not occured before, 0 prefix sum means whole sum till current index is divisible by k so 1 elligible subset [4, 5, 0, -2, -3, 1]
```
So, there are 7 subarrays with a sum divisible by k = 5:
 [5] , [5, 0] , [0] , [5, 0, -2, -3] , [0, -2, -3] , [-2, -3] , [4, 5, 0, -2, -3, 1]
```
class Solution {
public:
    int subarraysDivByK(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
        long long sum=0,count=0;
        vector<int> residueclass(k,0);
        for(auto &n:nums){
            sum+=n;
            int rem=sum%k;
            if(rem<0)rem+=k;
            count+=residueclass[rem];
            residueclass[rem]++;
        }
        count+=residueclass[0];
        return count;
    }
};
```

