solutions.content:
# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Compute the prefix sum for each element in the array. For each prefix sum value, if we divide it by k and compute the remainder, then we can conclude that a given sub array is divisible by k if the modulo value for the prefix sums at the beginning and ending index of the sub array have the same value.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1. Iterate over the `nums` array and keep a running sum count of the sum of all the elements so far. The sum at each index is the prefix sum for that index.
2. Divide each prefix sum by k and compute the remainder. If this value is negative, add k to it to change it to positive.
3. For each element of the input array we check if the current remainder value has been encountered before, and if so, how many times. We add that count to our total count of sub arrays divisible by k.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n)$$
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $$O(k)$$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
  public int subarraysDivByK(int[] nums, int k) {
    int prefixSum = 0;
    int ans = 0;
    int[] modulo = new int[k];

    for (int i=0; i < nums.length; i++) {
      prefixSum += nums[i];
      int key = prefixSum % k;

      // If the key is negative, add k to it to convert it to positive.
      key += key >= 0 ? 0 : k;

      ans += modulo[key];

      // key = 0 means that the currrent element by itself is divisible by k.
      // We handle this special case of a single element sub array by checking for this condition separately.
      ans += key == 0 ? 1 : 0;
      modulo[key]++;
    }
    return ans;
  }
}
```

