# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Use a prefix sum modulo `k` to count the subarrays that sum `0` modulo `k`.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Iterate the array indices `i` from 0 to n-1 while adding a prefix sum modulo `k` and consider the following non-exclusive two cases.
1.- When the subarray from `0` to `i`, sums to zero then add one to the answer.
2.- When we can remove a previous subarray to make the sum ending at `i` zero. In this case use a map, or an array to count the previous subarray values. If you find one that has the same sum as the current, then that means you can subtract that other subarray from the current and make it sum to zero.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n)$$ from iterating the array once
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $$O(k)$$ from storing k previous sums.
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
const subarraysDivByK = (nums, k)=>{
    const prevsums = Array(k).fill(0);
    const mod = (n, m)=> (n % m + m) % m;
    let ans = 0, prev = 0;
    for(const num of nums){
        prev = mod(prev + num, k)
        if(prev == 0) ans++;
        ans+=prevsums[prev];
        prevsums[prev]++;
    }
    return ans;
};
```

